{"cursor":"43389","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Chembox\n| verifiedrevid = 477003687 ImageFile = SiC p1390066.jpg ImageSize = 244\n| ImageName = Sample of silicon carbide as a boule PIN = Silicon carbide\n| OtherNames = Carborundum Moissanite Section1 = {{Chembox Identifiers\n| CASNo = 409-21-2 CASNo_Ref = PubChem = 9863 PubChem_Ref = ChemSpiderID = 9479\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = EINECS = 206-991-8 MeSHName = Silicon+carbide ChEBI_Ref =\n| ChEBI = 29390 RTECS = VW0450000 SMILES = [C-]#[Si+] StdInChI_Ref = StdInChI =\n| 1S/CSi/c1-2 InChI1 = 1/CSi/c1-2 StdInChIKey_Ref = StdInChIKey = HBMJWWWQQXIZIP-UHFFFAOYSA-\n| N InChIKey = HBMJWWWQQXIZIP-UHFFFAOYAF Gmelin = 13642\n }}\n| Section2 = {{Chembox Properties C = 1 Si = 1 ExactMass = gÂ·mol â1\n| Appearance = Colorless crystals Density = 3.21 gÂ·cm â3 (all\n| polytypes) MeltingPtC = 2730 Melting_notes = decomposes\n| ElectronMobility = ~900 cm 2/VÂ·s (all polytypes) RefractIndex = 2.55\n| (infrared; all polytypes)\n }}\n | Section7 = {{Chembox Hazards EUClass = Not listed NFPA-H = 1 NFPA-F = 0\n | NFPA-R = 0\n }} }} 'Silicon carbide' ('SiC'), also known as 'carborundum' , is a compound of\n silicon and carbon with chemical formula SiC. It occurs in nature as the\n extremely rare mineral moissanite. Silicon carbide powder has been mass-\n produced since 1893 for use as an abrasive. Grains of silicon carbide can be\n bonded together by sintering to form very hard ceramics which are widely used\n in applications requiring high endurance, such as car brakes, car clutches and\n ceramic plates in bulletproof vests. Electronic applications of silicon carbide\n as light emitting diodes (LEDs) and detectors in early radios were first\n demonstrated around 1907, and today SiC is widely used in high-temperature/high-\n voltage semiconductor electronics. Large single crystals of silicon carbide can\n be grown by the Lely method; they can be cut into gems known as synthetic\n moissanite. Silicon carbide with high surface area can be produced from\n SiO 2 contained in plant material.\n","linknr":782,"url":"Silicon_carbide","recorded":1362375643,"links":73,"instances":["1886","abrasive_cutting","metallurgy","materials_science","mechanical","meteorite","mineralogy","crystal_structure","metalworking","chemistry","electricity","body_armor","crystal_system"],"pdf":["http://www.nsc.co.jp/en/tech/report/pdf/8407.pdf","http://www.nsc.co.jp/en/tech/report/pdf/8407.pdf","http://www.iop.org/EJ/article/1468-6996/9/4/044204/stam8_4_044204.pdf","http://www.iop.org/EJ/article/1468-6996/9/4/044204/stam8_4_044204.pdf","http://www.iop.org/EJ/article/1468-6996/9/4/044205/stam8_4_044205.pdf","http://www.iop.org/EJ/article/1468-6996/9/4/044205/stam8_4_044205.pdf","http://www.iop.org/EJ/article/1468-6996/9/4/044201/stam8_4_044201.pdf","http://www.iop.org/EJ/article/1468-6996/9/4/044201/stam8_4_044201.pdf","http://www.physics.gatech.edu/npeg/publications/deHeerReviewfinal.pdf","http://www.physics.gatech.edu/npeg/publications/deHeerReviewfinal.pdf","http://www.physics.gatech.edu/npeg/publications/DeHeerSSC07.pdf","http://www.physics.gatech.edu/npeg/publications/DeHeerSSC07.pdf"],"categories":["Carbides","Inorganic silicon compounds","Semiconductor materials","Superhard materials","Ceramic materials","Refractory materials","Gemstones","Synthetic minerals","Deoxidizers","Abrasives"],"headings":["Discovery and early production","Natural occurrence","Production","Structure and properties","Uses","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4d/SiC_p1390066.jpg/244px-SiC_p1390066.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/fb/Yes_check.svg/7px-Yes_check.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/fb/Yes_check.svg/7px-Yes_check.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/fb/Yes_check.svg/7px-Yes_check.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/fb/Yes_check.svg/7px-Yes_check.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wiki